nth":8,"day":29,"city":"Woodbury","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00262","mother_id":"I00166"},"tags":["clergy","yale_connection"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 514"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00940","children_ids":["H01353","H01354","H01355","H01356"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1792,"date_month":6,"date_day":11,"location_city":"Stockbridge","location_state":"Massachusetts"}],"orbit_connections":[{"name":"Joseph Harvey (Yale 1809) — succeeded Asahel at Goshen","relationship":"Harvey succeeded Asahel Hooker as pastor at Goshen CT in 1810","notes":"Yale Biographical Sketches (Dexter): \"The Rev. Asahel Hooker (Yale 1789) was dismissed from his pastorate over the Congregational Church of Goshen, in Litchfield County, on June 12, 1810; and Mr. Harvey thereafter supplied the pulpit with such favor that he was unanimously called to the vacant place.\" Also: Joseph Edwards (Yale, graduated c.1806) \"began the study of theology upon graduation with the Rev. Asahel Hooker (Yale 1789), of Goshen, at the same time conducting an academy there.\" Asahel Hooker's Goshen pastorate was evidently a center of theological training in Litchfield County during the early 19th century. (Yale Biographical Sketches of Grads 1805-1815, Dexter 1912; URL: https://www.cga.ct.gov/hco/books/Biographical_Sketches_of_Grads_of_Yale_1805-1815_1912.pdf)","connection_type":"orbit_non_descendant"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"pastor of the church in Goshen until dismissed","primary_url":"https://www.cga.ct.gov/hco/books/Biographical_Sketches_of_Grads_of_Yale_1805-1815_1912.pdf","primary_url_label":"Source"},"death":{},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Asahel Hooker","first_name":"Asahel","maiden_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1789"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Eighteen years at Goshen, dismissed for ill health","body":"Asahel Hooker was ordained at Goshen, Connecticut on September 7, 1791, and served the congregation as beloved pastor for eighteen years. He was dismissed June 12, 1810 — not over doctrine or congregational conflict, but because his health had broken. Throughout his Goshen tenure he was a published voice in the Connecticut Evangelical Magazine."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Married Jonathan Edwards's granddaughter Phebe Edwards","body":"On June 11, 1792 he married Phebe Edwards (H00940), daughter of Hon. Timothy Edwards and granddaughter of Rev. Jonathan Edwards. Like Asahel, Phebe descended from Thomas Hooker — but through Mary Hooker Pierpont's line rather than the surname line. Their son Edward William Hooker would later write the 1849 biography of Thomas Hooker cited as the foundational source by Edward Hooker's 1909 Descendants."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"His son wrote the 1849 Thomas Hooker biography","body":"His son Rev. Edward William Hooker (H01354) wrote The Life of Rev. Thomas Hooker in 1849. The biography became the foundational source for nineteenth-century Hooker scholarship and was cited as a primary reference in Edward Hooker's 1909 Descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker. Edward William inherited the double Hooker descent — surname line through Asahel, Edwards line through his mother Phebe."}],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","dates":"1789","notes":" — Yale College 1789. Son of Asahel Hooker (H00262). Congregational pastor at Goshen CT 1791-1810, Norwich CT 1812-1813. Yale Biographical Sketches mention him as the pastor at Goshen when Joseph Harvey (Yale 1809) succeeded him and when Joseph Edwards (Yale student) studied theology with him."}],"slug":"asahel-hooker-1762"},"H00940":{"id":"H00940","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00381","mother_id":"X00709"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909"}],"birth":{"year":1768,"month":11,"day":4,"city":"Elizabethtown","state":"New Jersey"},"death":{"year":1848,"month":1,"day":22,"city":"Andover","state":"Massachusetts"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00514","children_ids":["H01353","H01354","H01355","H01356"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1792,"date_month":6,"date_day":11,"location_city":"Stockbridge","location_state":"Massachusetts"},{"spouse_id":"X00710","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":2,"date_year":1814,"date_month":10,"date_day":30}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Phebe Edwards","first_name":"Phebe","last_name":"Edwards","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"phebe-edwards-1768"},"H01353":{"id":"H01353","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00940","mother_id":"H00514"},"tags":["died_in_infancy"],"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909"}],"birth":{"year":1793,"month":9,"city":"Goshen","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1794},"gender":"male","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Timothy Edwards Hooker","first_name":"Timothy","last_name":"Hooker","middle_name":"Edwards","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"timothy-hooker-1793"},"H01354":{"id":"H01354","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00940","mother_id":"H00514"},"tags":["author","clergy","double_hooker_ancestry","middlebury_graduate","native_american_contact","temperance","educator","minister"],"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909"}],"birth":{"year":1794,"month":11,"day":24,"city":"Goshen","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1875,"month":3,"day":31,"city":"Fort Atkinson","state":"Wisconsin","country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00711","children_ids":["HD2241","HD2242","HD2243","HD2244","HD2245","HD2246"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1821,"location_country":"United States"},{"spouse_id":"X00712","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":2,"date_year":1850,"date_month":11,"date_day":19,"location_city":"Norwich","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States"}],"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Double Hooker descendant; ABCFM corporate member","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_William_Hooker"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"literature","header":"Wrote definitive 1849 biography of Thomas Hooker","body":"In 1849 he published 'The Life of Thomas Hooker' — the foundational biography of his Hartford-founding ancestor. Edward Hooker cited it as a primary authority sixty years later when compiling the 1909 Descendants of Rev Thomas Hooker — the genealogical spine of this entire project."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Hooker descendant through both parents independently","body":"His father descended from Thomas Hooker through the Hooker surname line, while his mother Phebe Edwards descended from the same ancestor through the separate Pierpont-Edwards line — making him a Hooker descendant twice over, through two parallel five-generation paths."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"ABCFM corporate member and Middlebury College trustee","body":"He served as a corporate member of the American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions from 1840 and as a trustee of Middlebury College from 1834 to 1844. The ABCFM was the leading Protestant foreign-mission engine of the antebellum era; his presence on the corporate board placed him at its strategic center."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Son Elias named for missionary brother-in-law","body":"He named one son Elias Cornelius Hooker for his brother-in-law Rev Elias Cornelius — the ABCFM missionary who had married his sister Mary Ann Hooker. The name kept the missionary calling visible in the next generation, even though Cornelius himself died young in 1832."}],"number_of_marriages":2,"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST054","institution_blurb":"Middlebury College alumnus."},{"institution_id":"INST041","institution_blurb":"Corporate member of ABCFM from 1840."},{"institution_id":"INST137","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1817","institution_blurb":"Andover Theological Seminary 1817 — ordained Green's Farms CT 1821."}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Edward William Hooker","first_name":"Edward","last_name":"Hooker","middle_name":"William","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://images.findagrave.com/photos/2013/307/96378384_138361708435.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"edward-hooker-1794"},"H01355":{"id":"H01355","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00940","mother_id":"H00514"},"tags":["double_hooker_ancestry","native_american_contact"],"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909"},{"short":"Cornelius genealogy book 1904","url":"https://archive.org/details/historyofcorneli00corn/page/n43/mode/2up","note":"History of Cornelius family; section 3-VI gives Elias Cornelius D.D. line"}],"birth":{"year":1796,"month":4,"day":17,"city":"Goshen","state":"Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00724","children_ids":["HD2296","HD2297","HD2298","HD2299","HD2300","HD2301"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1818,"date_month":9,"date_day":28,"location_city":"Somers","location_county":"Westchester County","location_state":"New York"}],"death":{"year":1880,"month":10,"day":17,"city":"Newton Center","state":"Massachusetts"},"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Wife of Elias Cornelius, ABCFM Indian Nations missionary"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Ann Hooker","first_name":"Mary","middle_name":"Ann","maiden_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST041","institution_blurb":"Wife of ABCFM Secretary Rev. Elias Cornelius (X00724), m. 1818."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Widowed at thirty-six, lived another forty-eight years","body":"Mary Ann Hooker married Elias Cornelius on September 28, 1818 at Somers, New York — an ABCFM missionary who worked among the Creek and Cherokee nations and published the first scholarly account of the Etowah Indian Mounds. He died in 1832, leaving her widowed at thirty-six. She lived another forty-eight years, dying at Newton Center, Massachusetts in 1880 at age eighty-four."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"A printing error aged her eleven years","body":"The Cornelius genealogy printed her birth as 1785 — an error her 1818 marriage at twenty-two disproves, and every other record corrects to 1796. Her husband’s first published account of the Etowah Indian Mounds and his choice of Elias Boudinot for the Foreign Mission School are part of the household story she carried for forty-eight widowed years."}],"slug":"mary-hooker-1796-2"},"H01356":{"id":"H01356","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00940","mother_id":"H00514"},"tags":["double_hooker_ancestry"],"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909"}],"birth":{"year":1803,"month":8,"day":28,"city":"Goshen","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1881},"gender":"female","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Elizabeth Hooker Reeve","first_name":"Sarah","last_name":"Reeve","maiden_name":"Hooker","middle_name":"Elizabeth","married_names":["Reeve"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"sarah-reeve-1803"},"H00515":{"id":"H00515","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1764,"month":8,"day":5,"city":"Woodbury","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00262","mother_id":"I00166"},"tags":["deacon","politician"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 515"}],"death":{"year":1826,"month":6,"day":22,"city":"Bristol","state":"Connecticut"},"nationally_prominent":false,"marriages":[{"children_ids":[],"spouse_id":"X01271","marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1804,"date_year":1790,"date_month":10,"date_day":7,"location_city":"Hartford","location_state":"Connecticut"},{"children_ids":["HD0606","HD0607","HD0608"],"spouse_id":"X01272","marriage_number":2,"date_year":1804,"location_city":"Bristol","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"primary_url":"https://goodwingenealogy.fandom.com/wiki/Bryan_Hooker_(Bristol_deacon)","primary_url_label":"Goodwin Genealogy","notable_blurb":"Woolen pioneer; 1818 Constitutional Convention delegate","notable_category":["business","politics"]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Bryan Hooker","first_name":"Bryan","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"Woolen pioneer and 1818 Constitution delegate","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781205983/Screenshot_2026-06-11_at_12.26.06_PM_imjx9x.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"business","header":"First Bristol woolen manufactory, burned 1903","body":"Bryan Hooker established one of the first woolen manufactories in Connecticut at Bristol — his fulling mill long known locally as 'the old yellow shop, near the bridge on the corner of East and South Streets.' The building stood for over a century before it was destroyed by fire in 1903 — seventy-seven years after Hooker's death. The mill represented the small-scale industrial transition between colonial-era home-spinning and the later New England textile factory system."},{"number":2,"category":"politics","header":"Delegate to 1818 Connecticut Constitution convention","body":"On July 4, 1818, Bryan Hooker was appointed delegate to the Hartford convention that framed the new Connecticut Constitution — the document that finally separated church and state in Connecticut and replaced the colonial-era Fundamental Orders. He had served Bristol as Town Clerk in 1806 and from 1811 through 1820, and as Bristol's representative in the Connecticut General Assembly across four sessions between 1812 and 1817. He voted on the conservative side and chaired several important committees during the convention."},{"number":3,"category":"business","header":"The old yellow shop by the bridge","body":"Bryan built one of the first woolen manufactories in Connecticut; his fulling mill at the corner of East and South Streets was known for generations as the old yellow shop. It outlived him by seventy-seven years, until fire took it in 1903."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"“Wouldn’t you like to see your mother?”","body":"His new stepdaughter, nine-year-old Rhoda Ann Fuller, boycotted the wedding and fled to her grandparents. On Esquire Hooker’s advice no one pursued her for a full year — then he drove his carriage over “on business,” asked the question, and she came home for good, staying until her own marriage to the mapmaker Samuel Augustus Mitchell."}],"career":[{"role":"Woolen manufacturer","location":"Bristol"},{"role":"Town Clerk","organization":"Bristol","start_year":1806,"end_year":1820},{"role":"Representative","organization":"Connecticut General Assembly"}],"slug":"bryan-hooker-1764"},"X01271":{"id":"X01271","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"gender":"female","number_of_marri